SIMPLE: gong
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gong
<hw>Gong</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>gong</ets>,
<ets>gang</ets>, a going, passage, drain. See <er>Gang</er>.]</ety>
<def>A privy or jakes.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Gong farmer</b></col>, <col><b>Gong
man</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a cleaner of privies.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gong</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gong
<hw>Gong</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <ety>[Malayan (Jav.)
<ets>g⟦omac⟧ng</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument, first used in the East,
made of an alloy of copper and tin, shaped like a disk with upturned
rim, and producing, when struck, a harsh and resounding noise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O'er distant deserts sounds the Tartar <qex>gong</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A flat saucerlike bell, rung by
striking it with a small hammer which is connected with it by various
mechanical devices; a stationary bell, used to sound calls or alarms; --
called also <altname>gong bell</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gong metal</b></col>, <cd>an alloy (78 parts of copper,
22 of tin), from which Oriental gongs are made.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gongorism</ent>⟦br⟧
